introduction.p:
Since the system is an ideal gas and the processes are all quasi-static it is possible to work out heat and work in each step as we will show below.  These calculations show that the ratio of  Q_C  to  Q_H   is equal to the ratio of the temperatures of the baths in absolute scale.

	\dfrac{Q_C}{Q_H} = \dfrac{T_C}{T_H}\ \ \text{(temperatures in kelvin scale)} 

This relation can also used to define the absolute or kelvin scale of temperature from an operational viewpoint. Using this equaiton we can deduce the following for  the efficiency of a Carnot engine.

	\eta_{\text{Carnot}}= 1-\dfrac{T_C}{T_H}\ \ \text{(temperatures in absolute/Kelvin scale)} 

This formula for the efficiency of a Carnot engine says that a Carnot engine will be 100% efficient only if the temperature of the cold bath  T_C  were zero degree kelvin.

solution.p:
(a) The efficiency of a Carnot engine can be written in terms of temperatures of the hot and cold baths. But, there is a catch. In order to make use of the formula for efficiency in terms of temperatures, we must express the temperatures in absolute scale.

	\amp T_H = 400 + 273.15 = 673.15\text{K} 
	\amp T_C = 27 + 273.15 = 300.15\text{K}


Therefore, the efficiency of the Carnot engine is

	\eta = 1- \dfrac{T_C}{T_H} = 1 - \dfrac{300.15\text{K}}{673.15\text{K}} = 0.554.

The efficiency in this formula is written as fraction.  Normally, we write the number in percentage by multiplying this number by 100.  This gives the efficiency of this engine to be 55.4%.

sidebyside.p:
First we find the (p,V) at the vertices of the cycle.

	 A:\ \ \amp  
	 \amp  T_A = 500\ \text{K}
	 \amp  V_A = 3\times 10^{-3}\ \text{m}^3
	 \amp  p_A = 2\times \frac{8.31\times 500}{3\times 10^{-3}} = 2.77\ \text{MPa}

solution.p:
C:

	 \amp  T_C = 300\ \text{K}
	 \amp  V_C^{\gamma-1} =\frac{T_B}{T_C}  V_B^{\gamma-1} \ \ \Longrightarrow\ \  V_C = 12.9\times 10^{-3}\ \text{m}^3
	 \amp  p_C =  \frac{2 \times 8.31\times 300}{12.9\times 10^{-3}} = 0.386\ \text{MPa}

D:

	 \amp  T_D = 300\ \text{K}
	 \amp  V_D^{\gamma-1} =\frac{T_A}{T_D}  V_A^{\gamma-1} \ \ \Longrightarrow\ \ V_D = 6.45\times 10^{-3}\ \text{m}^3
	 \amp  p_D V_D = p_C V_C \ \ \Longrightarrow\ \ p_D =    0.773\ \text{MPa}

The calculations for the work by the gas give.

	 \amp  W_{AB} = n R T_A \ln \frac{V_B}{V_A} = 5760\ \text{J}
	 \amp  W_{BC} =\frac{3 n}{2} R (T_B -T_C)  = 4986\ \text{J}
	 \amp  W_{CD} = n R T_C \ln \frac{V_D}{V_C} = - 3456\ \text{J}
	 \amp  W_{DA} =\frac{3 n}{2} R (T_D -T_A)  = -4986\ \text{J}

The net work for the entire cycle is obtained by adding the work in each step.

	W = 2304\ \text{J}.

The Carnot efficiency of the cycle is given by

	\eta = 1-\frac{300\ \text{K}}{500\ \text{K}} = 0.4.

Therefore the cycle abosrbs the following energy from the higher-temperature source.

	Q_{in} = \frac{W}{\eta} = \frac{2304\ \text{J}}{0.4} = 5760\ \text{J}.

This is same as the work done in the AB part of the cycle since the change in the internal energy for a constant temperature process of an ideal gas is zero.
